<br>
Yes, but you are confusing arguements.  Try separating them out some, and answering them separately.<br>
<br>
1.  I said capital punishment acts as a deterrent, in 2 ways: first, someone executed will NOT be a repeat offender, and second, it WILL make people think twice about the consequences of their actions.  Note that the second isn't all inclusive, and its nature makes it impossible to prove, other than as a basic principle of negative reinforcement.  If you want to argue the second isn't true, realize that you are also arguing that knowing you would be punished never prevents people from doing things - which I KNOW to be false, because I know that the only reason I haven't already killed a few people is because I don't want to be imprisoned, and they never passed the threshhold of being worth taking the risk and effort of disposing of the bodies.<br>
<br>
2.  People are biased, yes.  But it takes 12 people to agree, beyond any reasonable doubt, in someones guilt.  Perfect?  Not all all.  You have something better in mind?<br>
<br>
&quot;Explain to me how 4 white cops empty their guns into an innocent men for a total of 41 shots... and still go free?&quot;<br>
<br>
I don't know the situation you're referring to at all.  Without specifics, I'll treat it as a hypothetical.  A guy is on drugs, causing a disturbance.  Police are called, he gets violent.  He pulls a weapon (say, a large knife).  They shoot him, he keeps coming.  They shoot again, he keeps coming, and is very close now.  You're damn straight they would all unload on him.  I'd prolly drop several magazines in the guy myself.  There are some drugs that give people adrenaline and lack of feeling - they really don't stop until they are put down, and hard.  As for innocent?  If that were so, there would be publicity and riots . . . you're not giving the full story, if you say this really happened.<br>
<br>
&quot;As for the DNA test.. guess what.. those in favor of the death penalty are the ones against DNA testing...&quot;<br>
<br>
There you go, making gross (and false) generalizations.  I'm in favor of both.  <br>
<br>
&quot;As for the DNA test.. guess what.. those in favor of the death penalty are the ones against DNA testing...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;More than one prosecutor is opposed to having their cases examined using DNA evience . . .&quot;<br>
<br>
So, someone that is making an arguement wants to ignore evidence for the arguement of the other side?  DUH.  Thats always true of any arguement, debate, trial.  Defense attorneys get all sorts of evidence thrown out all the time.  Thats why we have an objective party (aka a judge) decide what is permissible - just like debates have moderators.<br>
<br>
&quot;So if it doesn't matter if an innocent person is put to death.. why bother with trial and other fanfare? why not execute everyone that gets arrested and safe the money of the trial?&quot;<br>
<br>
Who here said it doesn't matter?  Who said we should kill them before a trial?  Don't put words in peoples mouths, and then attack things they didn't say; it doesn't help your position at all.<br>
<br>
Since you brought a specific up, so will I: Charlie Manson.  NO ONE would question his guilt, or the extent of his crimes . . . so why not execute him?<br>
